  "prompt": "Does the government have laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, the U.S. government has several laws against money laundering. The primary ones are:\n\n*   **The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)**: This act requires financial institutions to keep records and file reports on transactions that might indicate money laundering, tax evasion, or other criminal activities.\n\n*   **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**: This act made money laundering a federal crime.\n\n*   **USA PATRIOT Act of 2001**: This act strengthened anti-money laundering laws, in part to combat terrorism financing.\n\nThese laws and others provide a framework for preventing, detecting, and prosecuting money laundering activities. Other countries have their own laws against money laundering as well, and there are also international efforts to combat money laundering.",
